<div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-8 lg:gap-4 lg:grid-cols-13 mt-12 lg:mt-16 mb-24">
    <div class="lg:col-span-6 text-keynote-400">
        <!-- em-width space -->
        <p id="now">&#8195;</p>
        <p id="last-fm">&#8195;</p>
    </div>

    <div class="hidden absolute w-[18vw] lg:w-[16rem] top-32 right-4 lg:left-4 md:flex flex-row-reverse lg:flex-row gap-1 lg:items-end">
        <img src="/img/me.jpg" alt="A picture of me, taken by Claire S. Burke." />
        <p class="text-keynote-400 bg-white" style="writing-mode: vertical-rl; text-orientation: mixed;">
            Photo by
            <a href="https://www.burkesclaire.com/" class="underline hover:text-keynote-700">Claire S. Burke</a>
        </p>
    </div>

    <p class="font-xanh text-lg lg:col-span-7 max-w-prose text-keynote-700">
    I'm David (they/them), and I'm a PhD student in Computer Science with a Designated Emphasis in New Media at UC Berkeley, advised by
    <a class="underline hover:text-keynote-400" href="https://schasins.com">Sarah E. Chasins</a>.
    </p>

    <p class="font-plex lg:col-start-7 lg:col-span-7 max-w-prose text-keynote-700">
    Broadly, I'm thinking about how to use the methods of Third World liberation movement work to inform how we think about programming. Right now, my work looks like building novel direct manipulation programming tools, writing on the history of programming languages and queer digital spaces, building digital archives with Asian American movement OGs, and working alongside legal advocates and archivists.
    </p>
</div>

